<DOC><DOCNO> AP901029-0138 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-10-29-90 1724EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Gulf 1stLd-Writethru a0671 10-29 0288</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Israel-Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,0337</SECOND><HEAD>Shamir Warns Iraq Not to `Lay A Finger on Israel'</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD Israeli stopover not on Baker agenda,details. No pickup</NOTE><DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir warned Iraq onMonday not to ``lay a finger on Israel'' lest Saddam Hussein ``paya terrible price for his blunder.''   Shamir told Jewish fundraisers at the Hyatt Regency Hotel inJerusalem, ``Our very presence in this region, thanks to our strongwill and capacity, (has) been and continues to be a force forstability, a barrier that prevented many military adventures andmuch more violence.''   He reassured the audience that Iraqi President Saddam's attemptsto coax Israel into the conflict in the Persian Gulf would fail.   ``Saddam Hussein must surely know that if he lays a finger onIsrael he will pay a terrible price for such a blunder,'' Shamirsaid. ``This attempt to drag us into the present conflict ... willnot succeed.''   Earlier, Finance Minister Yitzhak Modai announced economicreforms that included an additional military budget of aquarter-billion dollars in light of the gulf crisis, Israel armyradio said.   Saddam has repeatedly threatened to torch Israel with binarychemical weapons. His first threat came in April when he said hewould to use chemical weapons in answer to an Israeli nuclearattack. He later said an American attack would also lead to anattack on Israel.   The Israeli government has taken these threats seriously and hasdistributed gas mask kits to the general public.   Meanwhile, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said he doesnot expect to visit Israel on his trip to the Middle East andEurope starting Friday.   Baker, who will use the trip to consult on the gulf crisis, tolda gathering in Los Angeles a stopover in Israel would leave theimpresion there is a linkage between the Arab-Israeli conflict andthe gulf crisis.   ``We are very anxious that there not be a linkage,'' Baker said.</TEXT></DOC>